# Section 11 — Complete Debugging Journey & Engineering Decisions

---

# 11.1 Introduction

Software engineering is not simply writing code.

It is the process of identifying problems, forming hypotheses, testing assumptions, eliminating possibilities, and eventually converging on the correct solution.

The Study Abroad Finder project was intentionally developed using an incremental debugging strategy.

Rather than attempting to solve multiple unknowns simultaneously, every subsystem was validated independently.

This chapter documents that complete engineering journey.

---

# 11.2 Engineering Philosophy

The project followed one fundamental debugging principle.

> Never debug multiple unknowns simultaneously.

Instead,

every experiment should answer only one question.

For example

```
Does Gemini work?
```

NOT

```
Does Gemini + Maps + Tavily + Scholarship + Filesystem work?
```

This philosophy dramatically reduced debugging complexity.

---

# 11.3 Original Assumption

Initially,

it was assumed that

```
Works Locally

↓

Will Work on Render
```

This assumption proved incorrect.

One of the most important lessons from the project is that

> Application code and execution environment are equally important.

---

# 11.4 First Local Success

The first milestone was obtaining a successful local execution.

The application correctly:

- Loaded Flask
- Connected to Gemini
- Loaded MCP servers
- Generated responses
- Produced Markdown reports

At this point,

the application architecture itself appeared correct.

---

# 11.5 First Render Deployment

The application was deployed using Render's default Python runtime.

Observations:

✓ UI Loaded

✓ Gunicorn Started

✓ Flask Started

✗ AI Requests Failed

This immediately suggested

the deployment environment differed from local execution.

